 spending, OECD<ref name=SSP2015/>\n!Country !! Public social spending<br />% of GDP\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| FRA}} || 31.7\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| FIN}} || 30.6\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| BEL}} || 29.2\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| ITA}} || 28.9\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| DNK}} || 28.8\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| AUT}} || 28.0\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| SWE}} || 26.7\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| GRC}} || 26.4\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| ESP}} || 25.4\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| DEU}} || 25.0\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| PRT}} || 24.1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| NOR}} || 23.9\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| SVN}} || 22.4\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| NLD}} || 22.3\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| LUX}} || 22.2\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| GBR}} || 21.5\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|OECD || 21.0\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| HUN}} || 20.7\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| NZL}} || 19.7\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| CHE}} || 19.6\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| CZE}} || 19.5\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| POL}} || 19.4\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| SVK}} || 19.4\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| USA}} || 19.0\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| AUS}} || 18.8\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| CAN}} || 17.2\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| EST}} || 17.0\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| IRL}} || 17.0\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| ISR}} || 16.0\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| ISL}} || 15.7\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| LVA}} || 14.4\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| CHL}} || 11.2\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry| KOR}} || 10.1\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Rahn curve]]\n* [[Government operations]]\n* [[Public expenditure]]\n* [[Public finance]]\n* [[Government budget]]\n* [[Government waste]]\n* [[Fiscal policy]]\n* [[Tax]]\n* [[Mandatory spending]]\n* [[Taxpayer groups|Taxpayers unions]]\n* [[Eurostat]]\n* [[Government spending in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[Government spending in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{notelist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Government Spending}}{{Commons|Public expenditure}}\n* [http://stats.oecd.org/Index.aspx?DataSetCode=SNA_TABLE11 OECD Government spending statistics]\n* [http://etatscanadiens-canadiangovernments.enap.ca/fr/index.aspx Canadian Governments Compared]\n* [http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/statistics-explained/index.php/Government_expenditure_by_function_%E2%80%93_COFOG Eurostat's government spending per sector]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2011}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Government Spending}}\n[[Category:Government spending]]\n[[Category:Government finances]]\n[[Category:Fiscal policy]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Government consumptions, investments, and transfer payments}}\n{{Redirect2|Public Purse|Public money|the term used in relation to the British monarchy|Privy Purse|the academic journal formerly called Public Money|Public Money & Management}}\n{{Public finance}}'''Government spending''' or '''expenditure''' includes all government consumption, investment, and transfer payments.<ref>{{cite web|title=Frequently Asked Questions: BEA seems to have several different measures of government spending. What are they for and what do they measure?|url=https://www.bea.gov/faq/index.cfm?faq_id=552|publisher=Bureau of Economic Analysis|accessdate=12 July 2014|date=28 May 2010}}</ref><ref>Robert Barro and Vittorio Grilli (1994), ''European Macroeconomics'', Ch. 15\u201316. Macmillan, {{ISBN|0-333-57764-7}}.</ref> In [[national income accounting]] the acquisition by governments of goods and services for current use, to directly satisfy the individual or collective needs of the community, is classed as [[government final consumption expenditure]]. Government acquisition of goods and services [[Investment#In economics or macroeconomics|intended to create future benefits]], such as infrastructure investment or research spending, is classed as government investment (government [[Gross fixed capital formation|gross capital formation]]). These two types of government spending, on final consumption and on gross capital formation, together constitute one of the major components of [[gross domestic product]].\n\nGovernment spending can be financed by government [[government debt|borrowing]], or [[taxes]]. Changes in government spending is a major component of [[fiscal policy]] used to stabilize the macroeconomic [[business cycle]].\n\n==Macroeconomic fiscal policy==\n{{main|fiscal policy}}\n[[File:Figure A - Crowding Out.jpg|thumb|620x620px|The Market for Capital (the Loanable Funds Market) and the Crowding Out Effect. An increase in government deficit spending \"crowds out\" private investment by increasing interest rates and lowering the quantity of capital available to the private sector.]]\nGovernment spending can be a useful economic policy tool for governments. [[Fiscal policy]] can be defined as the use of government spending and/or [[taxation]] as a mechanism to influence an economy.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite book|title=Principles of Economics|last=Gregory|first=Mankiw|publisher=Southwestern Publishing Group|year=2014|isbn=9781285165875|edition= Seventh |location=Stamford, CT|pages=|oclc=884664951}}</ref> There are two types of fiscal policy: expansionary fiscal policy, and contractionary fiscal policy. Expansionary fiscal policy is an increase in government spending or a decrease in taxation, while contractionary fiscal policy is a decrease in government spending or an increase in taxes. Expansionary fiscal policy can be used by governments to stimulate the economy during a [[recession]]. For example, an increase in government spending directly increases [[demand]] for goods and services, which can help increase [[Output (economics)|output]] and [[employment]]. On the other hand, contractionary fiscal policy can be used by governments to cool down the economy during an economic boom. A decrease in government spending can help keep [[inflation]] in check.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Principles of Macroeconomics: Economics and the Economy|last=Taylor|first=Timothy|publisher=Textbook Media Press|year=2017|isbn=9780996996334|edition= Fourth |location=Minneapolis|pages=366\u2013340|oclc=1001342630}}</ref> During economic downturns, in the short run, government spending can be changed either via [[Automatic stabilizer|automatic stabilization]] or discretionary stabilization. Automatic stabilization is when existing policies automatically change government spending or taxes in response to economic changes, without the additional passage of laws.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> A primary example of an [[automatic stabilizer]] is [[Unemployment Insurance|unemployment insurance]], which provides financial assistance to unemployed workers. Discretionary stabilization is when a government takes actions to change government spending or taxes in direct response to changes in the economy. For instance, a government may decide to increase government spending as a result of a recession.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Public Finance and Public Policy|last=Jonathan|first=Gruber|publisher=Worth Publishers|isbn=9781464143335|edition= Fifth |location=New York|pages=|oclc=914290290|date = 28 December 2015}}</ref> With discretionary stabilization, the government must pass a new law to make changes in government spending.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[John Maynard Keynes]] was one of the first [[economists]] to advocate for government [[deficit spending]] as part of the [[fiscal policy]] response to an [[recession|economic contraction]]. According to [[Keynesian economics]], increased government spending raises [[aggregate demand]] and increases [[Consumption (economics)|consumption]], which leads to increased production and faster recovery from recessions. [[Classical economists]], on the other hand, believe that increased government spending exacerbates an [[recession|economic contraction]] by shifting resources from the private sector, which they consider productive, to the public sector, which they consider unproductive.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Macroeconomics for Today|last=Irvin|first=Tucker|publisher=Cengage Learning|year=2012|isbn=9781133435051|edition= 8th |location=Mason, OH|pages=|oclc=830731890}}</ref>\n\nIn [[economics]], the potential \"shifting\" in resources from the [[private sector]] to the [[public sector]] as a result of an increase in government [[deficit spending]] is called [[Crowding out (economics)|crowding out]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The figure to the right depicts the market for capital, otherwise known as the market for [[loanable funds]]. The downward sloping [[demand curve]] D1 represents demand for private capital by [[firm]]s and [[investor]]s, and the upward sloping [[supply curve]] S1 represents savings by private individuals. The initial equilibrium in this market is represented by point A, where the equilibrium quantity of capital is K1 and the equilibrium interest rate is R1. If the government increases [[deficit spending]], it will borrow money from the private [[capital market]] and reduce the supply of savings to S2. The new equilibrium is at point B, where the interest rate has increased to R2 and the quantity of capital available to the private sector has decreased to K1. The government has essentially made borrowing more expensive and has taken away savings from the market, which \"crowds out\" some private investment. The crowding out of private investment could limit the economic growth from the initial increase government spending.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":8\" />\n\n=== Heterodox Economics disagrees ===\nThe above \"explanation\" comes from conventional, neoclassical, neoliberal economics, a \"discipline\" that did not predict the largest economic event of the last 80 years (the Global Financial Crisis, or sub-prime mortgage derivatives meltdown). There is very little empirical evidence that it works at all, so one must take it with a grain, if not a kilogram of salt.\n\nAs Matt Stoller says such economics \u201cis to create a language and methodology for governing that hides political assumptions from the public\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mattstoller.substack.com/p/what-is-the-point-of-economics|title=What Is the Point of Economics?|last=Stoller|first=Matt|website=mattstoller.substack.com|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nThe elaborate myths it promotes are things like \"crowding out,\" which presumes the economy is a zero-sum game. If that were true, then resources would always be 100% utilized, so if the government employs additional resources, it must do so at the expense of the private sector. But the economy, as of this writing, is only 77% employed, and as the coronavirus epidemic proceeds, that figure is going to be much lower. A sensible economist would conclude that government spending would employ idle resources, not \"crowd out\" private use of those resources.\n\nAnd that is exactly what history demonstrates: GDP growth spikes for the New Deal and that big public works project we call \"World War II,\" because those resources un- or under-employed during the Great Depression were brought back into production.\n\nThe mistaken conclusion is that government competes for savings, too. \"If government tries to borrow more by issuing and selling more bonds, then the competition for finance would push up interest rates. Some private firms would decide not to borrow at the higher rates and hence investment would be lower. Also, durable consuption expenditure by households will decline because some of it is financed by borrowing.\n\n\"However, that model is incorrect. Government fiscal deficits generate non-government surpluses (flows) that accumulate to the non-government sector's net acquisition of financial assets (a stock)... Since there are more savings (as a result of higher income levels arising from the deficits) and greater financial wealth, it is not true that government is competing with private sector borrowers for a limited supply of savings (a flow) to place government bonds into wealth portfolios that are fixed in size. Both savings and portfolios expand as government deficits grow.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=Mitchell, William, 1952-|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/967762036|title=Macroeconomics|others=Wray, L. Randall, 1953-, Watts, Martin, 1949-|isbn=1-137-61066-2|location=London|oclc=967762036}}</ref> And contrariwise, as government practices austerity, savings shrink and economic instability grows. Historically, whenever government has succumbed to the siren song of \"fiscal responsibility[tm]\" and significantly reduced deficits, the economy goes into a tailspin...100% of the time<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/the-federal-budget-is-not_b_457404|title=The Federal Budget Is Not Like a Household Budget: Here's Why|last=R|first=L.|last2=Wray|first2=all|date=2010-04-12|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17|last3=Economics|first3=ContributorProfessor of|last4=Employment|first4=Research Director of the Center for Full|last5=Stability|first5=Price|last6=City|first6=University of Missouri-Kansas}}</ref>!\n\nPerhaps most convincing is the failure of the neoclassicals to predict bad economic consequences for larger government 'debt.' Government 'debt' is nothing like household debt, it's like bank debt. If you have a bank account, that is your asset, but to the bank, it's a liability. Reducing the bank's debt reduces the depositors' savings. \n\nAccording to the neoclassicals, there's a threshold for government debt, beyond which the economy suffers, and bond markets demand higher interest rates, or they won't buy the debt. People often point to Greece as an example--but Greece no longer makes its own currency, so it isn't comparable to a monetary sovereign. Economists Reinhart and Rogoff tried to convince economists that government 'debt' larger than 90% of GDP impaired economic performance--until others examined their work found they cherry-picked their examples, and even had a mistake in the spreadsheet formulas they used to calculate this result.\n\nWhat is comparable to the monetary sovereign U.S. situation is Japan's. Japan makes the fiat currency called 'Yen,' and has a floating exchange rate. Its 'debt'-to-GDP ratio is 240%. The neoclassicals would say they certainly have borrowed too much, so the bond markets will charge a risk premium (higher interest rates) before they can sell Yen-denominated bonds. The truth is that the Bank of Japan's debt sells at near a zero interest rate. \n\n== Current use: final consumption expenditure ==\n{{Main|Government final consumption expenditure}}\n\nGovernment acquisition of goods and services for current use to directly satisfy individual or collective needs of the members of the community is called government final consumption expenditure (GFCE.) It is a purchase from the national accounts \"use of income account\" for goods and services directly satisfying of individual needs (''individual consumption'') or collective needs of members of the community (''collective consumption''). GFCE consists of the value of the goods and services produced by the government itself other than own-account [[capital formation]] and sales and of purchases by the government of goods and services produced by market producers that are supplied to households\u2014without any transformation\u2014as \"social transfers\" in kind.<ref>F. Lequiller, D. Blades: Understanding National Accounts, Paris: OECD 2006, pp. 127\u201330</ref>\n\n== National defense spending ==\n{{see also|Military budget|List of countries by military expenditures}}\n\nThe United States spends vastly more than other countries on national defense. The table below shows the top 10 countries with largest military expenditures as of 2015, the most recent year with publicly available data. As the table suggests, the United States spent nearly 3 times as much on the military than [[China]], the country with the next largest military spending. The U.S. military budget dwarfed spending by all other countries in the top 10, with 8 out of countries spending less than $100 billion in 2016.\n{| style=\"font-size:100%;\"\n|-\n|  style=\"width:50%; text-align:center;\"| '''List by the [[Stockholm International Peace Research Institute]]<br>''2017 Fact Sheet'' (for 2016)''<ref name=\"SIPRI\">{{cite web |url = https://www.sipri.org/sites/default/files/Trends-world-military-expenditure-2016.pdf |title = Trends in World Military Expenditure, 2016  |publisher = [[Stockholm International Peace Research Institute]] |accessdate= 24 April 2017}}</ref>''<br>SIPRI Military Expenditure Database<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sipri.org/sites/default/files/Milex-constant-2015-USD.pdf|title=Data for all countries from 1988\u20132016 in constant (2015) USD (pdf)|publisher=SIPRI|accessdate=24 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto\"\n|-  style=\"background:#ececec;\"\n! Rank !! Country !! Spending <br> (US$ Bn.) !! % of [[List of countries by GDP (nominal)|GDP]]\n|-\n||| '''World total ''' || align=right| '''1,686''' || align=right| '''2.2'''\n|-\n| {{0}}1  || align=left| {{flagicon|United States}} [[United States Armed Forces|United States]] || align=right| 611.2 || align=right| 3.3\n|-\n| {{0}}2   || align=left| {{flagicon|China}} [[People's Liberation Army|China, P.R.]]<ref name=\"x\">SIPRI estimate.</ref> || align=right| 215.7  || align=right| 1.9\n|-\n| {{0}}3   || align=left| {{flagicon|Russia}}  [[Russian Armed Forces|Russia]] || align=right| 69.2  || align=right| 5.3\n|-\n| {{0}}4  || align=left| {{flagicon|Saudi Arabia}} [[Armed Forces of Saudi Arabia|Saudi Arabia]]<ref name=\"x\"/><ref name=\"y\">The figures for Saudi Arabia include expenditure for public order and safety and might be slightly overestimated.</ref> || align=right| 63.7 || align=right| 10\n|-\n| {{0}}5  || align=left| {{flagicon|India}} [[Indian Armed Forces|India]] || align=right| 55.9 || align=right| 2.5\n|-\n| {{0}}6  || align=left| {{flagicon|France}} [[French Armed Forces|France]] || align=right| 55.7 || align=right| 2.3\n|-\n| {{0}}7   || align=left| {{flagicon|Great Britain}} [[British Armed Forces|United Kingdom]] || align=right| 48.3 || align=right| 1.8\n|-\n| {{0}}8   || align=left| {{flagicon|Japan}} [[Japan Self-Defense Forces|Japan]]|| align=right| 46.1 || align=\"right\" | 1.0\n|-\n| {{0}}9   || align=left| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Bundeswehr|Germany]] || align=right| 41.1 || align=right| 1.2\n|-\n| 10  || align=left| {{flagicon|South Korea}} [[Republic of Korea Armed Forces|South Korea]] || align=right| 36.8 || align=right| 2.7\n|}\n|}\n\n== Healthcare and medical research ==\n\nResearch Australia<ref>{{cite web|url=http://crm.researchaustralia.org/documents/item/84|title=Research Australia|author=|date=|website=crm.researchaustralia.org}}</ref> found 91% of Australians think \u2018improving hospitals and the health system\u2019 should be the Australian Government\u2019s first spending priority. \n\nCrowding 'in' also<ref>http://www.nber.org/papers/w15146.pdf</ref> happens in university life science research Subsidies, funding and government business or projects like this are often justified on the basis of their positive return on investment. Life science crowding in contrasts with crowding out in public funding of research more widely:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://oldblog.robwiblin.com/2012/09/25/measuring-the-additionally-of-grants-and-subsidies/|title=Do innovation programs actually increase innovation?|author=|date=24 September 2012|website=robwiblin.com}}</ref> \u201c10% increase in government R&D funding reduced private R&D expenditure by 3%...In Australia the average cost of public funds is estimated to be $1.20 and $1.30 for each dollar raised (Robson, 2005). The marginal cost is probably higher, but estimates differ widely depending on the tax that is increased.\u201d\n\n== Infrastructure and investment: gross fixed capital formation ==\n{{Main|Gross fixed capital formation}}\n{{Further|Investment#In economics or macroeconomics}}\n\nGovernment acquisition intended to create future benefits, such as infrastructure investment or research spending, is called gross fixed capital formation, or government investment, which usually is the largest part of the government.<ref name=eugcf>[http://epp.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/statistics_explained/index.php/Gross_capital_formation \"Gross capital formation\"] ''Statistics Explained'' European Union Statistics Directorate, European Commission</ref> Acquisition of goods and services is made through production by the government (using the government's labour force, fixed assets and purchased goods and services for [[intermediate consumption]]) or through purchases of goods and services from market producers. In [[economic theory]] or in [[macroeconomics]], investment is the amount purchased per unit of time of [[Good (economics and accounting)|goods]] which are not consumed but are to be used for future production (i.e. [[Capital (economics)|capital]]). Examples include [[railroad]] or [[factory]] construction.\n\n[[Infrastructure]] spending is considered government [[investment]] because it will usually save money in the long run, and thereby reduce the [[net present value]] of government liabilities.\n\nSpending on [[physical infrastructure]] in the U.S. returns an average of about $1.92 for each $1.00 spent on nonresidential construction because it is almost always less expensive to maintain than repair or replace once it has become unusable.<ref>{{Cite report |first= Isabelle |last= Cohen |first2= Thomas |last2= Freiling |first3= Eric |last3= Robinson |date= January 2012 |title= ''The Economic Impact and Financing of Infrastructure Spending'' |type= report |publisher= Thomas Jefferson Program in Public Policy, College of William & Mary |location= Williamsburg, Virginia |url= http://www.aednet.org/government/pdf-2012/infrastructure_report.pdf |page= 5 |accessdate= 1 October 2012 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120503233918/http://www.aednet.org/government/pdf-2012/infrastructure_report.pdf |archivedate= 3 May 2012 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nLikewise, government spending on [[Infrastructure#Social infrastructure|social infrastructure]], such as [[preventative health care]], can save several hundreds of billions of dollars per year in the U.S., because for example [[cancer]] patients are more likely to be diagnosed at [[Cancer staging|Stage I]] where curative treatment is typically a few outpatient visits, instead of at [[Cancer staging|Stage III]] or later in an [[emergency room]] where treatment can involve years of hospitalization and is often terminal.<ref>{{Cite journal\n| last1 = Hogg | first1 = W.\n| last2 = Baskerville | first2 = N.\n| last3 = Lemelin | first3 = J.\n| title = Cost savings associated with improving appropriate and reducing inappropriate preventive care: Cost-consequences analysis\n| journal = BMC Health Services Research\n| volume = 5\n| issue = 1\n| pages = 20\n| year = 2005\n| doi = 10.1186/1472-6963-5-20\n| pmid = 15755330\n| pmc =1079830\n}}</ref>\n\n== Transfer payment spending ==\n{{Main|Transfer payment}}\n\nGovernment expenditures that are not acquisition of goods and services, and which represent transfers of money such as [[social security]] payments, are called transfer payments. These payments are considered to be non-exhaustive{{technical statement|date=May 2014}} because they do not directly absorb [[Factors of production|resources]] or create [[Output (economics)|output]]. In other words, transfers are made without an exchange of goods or services.<ref>{{cite web\n|url= http://www.economist.com/economics-a-to-z/t#node-21529382\n|title=Economics AZ\u2013 terms beginning with T;transfer\n|first= Matthew\n|last=Bishop\n|work=The Economist\n|year=2012\n|quote=Payments that are made without any good or service being received in return. Much PUBLIC SPENDING goes on transfers, such as pensions and WELFARE benefits. Private-sector transfers include charitable donations and prizes to lottery winners. |accessdate=11 July 2012}}</ref> Examples of certain transfer payments include [[welfare (financial aid)]], [[social security]], and government giving [[Subsidy|subsidies]] to certain [[business]]es (firms).\n\n== Per capita spending ==\nIn 2010 national governments spent an average of $2,376 per person, while the average for the world's 20 largest economies (in terms of GDP) was $16,110 per person. Norway and Sweden expended the most at $40,908 and $26,760 per capita respectively. The federal government of the United States spent $11,041 per person. Other large economy country spending figures include South Korea ($4,557), Brazil ($2,813), Russia ($2,458), China ($1,010), and India ($226).<ref>CIA World Factbook, population data from 2010, Spending and GDP data from 2011. Note: these numbers do not include U.S. state and local government spending which when included bring the per capita spending to $16,755</ref> The figures below of 42% of GDP spending and a GDP per capita of $54,629 for the U.S. indicate a total per person spending including national, state, and local governments was $22,726 in the U.S.\n\n== As a percentage of GDP ==\n{{See also|List of countries by government spending as percentage of GDP}}[[File:Tax Burden as a Percentage of GDP (2014 Index of Economic Freedom).svg|thumb|550x550px|Tax Burden as a Percentage of GDP (2014 [[Index of Economic Freedom]]).<ref name=\"2014 Index of Economic Freedom\" />]] [[File:Depense-publique-sur-PIB.png|thumb|Public spending / GDP in Europe.<br />Legend: maroon > 55%, red 50\u201355%, orange 45\u201350%, yellow 40\u201345%, green 35\u201340%, blue 30\u201335%|450x450px]]This is a list of countries by government spending as a percentage of [[gross domestic product]] (GDP) for the listed countries, according to the ''2014 [[Index of Economic Freedom]]''<ref name=\"2014 Index of Economic Freedom\">{{cite web|url=http://www.heritage.org/index/explore?view=by-variables|title=Economic Data and Statistics on World Economy and Economic Freedom|author=|date=|website=www.heritage.org}}</ref> by [[The Heritage Foundation]] and ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''. [[Tax revenue]] is included for comparison. These statistics utilize the United Nations\u2019 System of National Accounts (SNA), which measures the government sector differently than the U.S. Bureau of Economic Analysis (BEA).\u00a0The SNA counts as government spending the gross cost of public services such as state universities and public hospitals.\u00a0For example, the SNA counts the entire cost of running the public-university system, not just what legislators appropriate to supplement students\u2019 tuition payments.\u00a0Those adjustments push up the SNA\u2019s measure of spending by roughly 4 percent of GDP compared with the standard\u00a0measure tallied by the BEA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbpp.org/blog/is-government-spending-really-41-percent-of-gdp|title=Is Government Spending Really 41 Percent of GDP?|date=2011-10-18|website=Center on Budget and Policy Priorities|language=en|access-date=2019-05-17}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+List of Countries as a % of GDP.\n|-\n! Country !! Tax burden % GDP !! Govt. expend. % GDP\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Afghanistan}} || 9 || 23\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Albania}} || 23 || 28\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Algeria}} || 10 || 40\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Angola}} || 6 || 39\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Argentina}} || 35 || 41\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Armenia}} || 17 || 25\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Australia}} || 26 || 35\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Austria}} || 42 || 51\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Azerbaijan}} || 13 || 34\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Bahamas}} || 16 || 23\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Bahrain}} || 3 || 31\n|