-tv-taking-part-bbc-one-show-12558735/ |accessdate=23 April 2020 |work=Metro |date=15 April 2020 }}</ref> to support those affected by the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"Metro-12521241\">{{cite web |title=Children In Need and Comic Relief join forces for first time for coronavirus |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/07/children-need-comic-relief-join-forces-first-time-coronavirus-relief-12521241/ |website=Metro |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Independent-a9474766\">{{cite news |title=BBC Big Night In: Peter Kay, Little Britain and Vicar of Dibley to return for special charity event - follow live |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/bbc-big-night-in-live-stream-channel-best-bits-peter-kay-little-britain-catch-up-watch-a9474766.html |accessdate=23 April 2020 |work=The Independent |date=23 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The British government will match all public donations, with a minimum of \u00a320 million.<ref name=\"BBC-52379802\">{{cite web |title=Doctor Who stars unite for BBC's Big Night In |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-52379802 |website=BBC News |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt is the first joint initiative between two BBC telethon charities, [[Children in Need]] and [[Comic Relief]].<ref name=\"Metro-12521241\" /> The [[showrunner]] and [[executive producer]] for the BBC is Peter Davey.<ref name=\"YLG2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.yourlocalguardian.co.uk/leisure/showbiz/18400491.foo-fighters-praise-live-lounge-charity-cover-ahead-bbcs-big-night/|title=Foo Fighters praise Live Lounge charity cover ahead of BBC\u2019s Big Night In|work=Your Local Guardian|accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Presenters and performers ==\nThe scheduled presenters include [[Lenny Henry]], [[Matt Baker]], [[Zoe Ball]], [[Davina McCall]] and [[Paddy McGuinness]].<ref name=\"Metro-12558735\" /> Most of those appearing will take part remotely, via [[Videotelephony|video links]], while the studio presenters will maintain [[social distancing]].<ref name=\"Independent-a9474766\" /> There will be comedy appearances by [[Steve Coogan]], [[Rob Brydon]], [[Jack Whitehall]], [[Romesh Ranganathan]], and [[Miranda Hart]],<ref name=\"BBC-52379802\" /> as well as music performances from [[Sam Smith]] and [[Celeste (singer)|Celeste]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/bignightin/theshow|title=Big Night In: The Show|website=BBC|url-status=live|access-date=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Line-up ==\nExcluding surprise appearances from guests like [[Mary Berry]] and [[Little Mix]], [[BBC]]'s final line-up is as follows:<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Metro-12558735\" /><ref name=\"ES-LB\">{{cite web |title=Little Britain to return to TV for Big Night In charity telethon |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/stayingin/tvfilm/little-britain-comeback-big-night-in-bbc-a4416191.html |website=Evening Standard |accessdate=23 April 2020 |date=16 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC-52379802\" /><ref name=\"Beaumont-Thomas\">{{cite news |last1=Beaumont-Thomas |first1=Ben |title=BBC Radio 1 launches coronavirus charity song with Dua Lipa, Chris Martin and more |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/20/bbc-radio-1-launches-coronavirus-charity-song-with-dua-lipa-chris-martin-and-more |accessdate=23 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n* [[Miranda Hart]] and the cast of ''[[Miranda (TV series)|Miranda]].''\n* A lockdown sermon by ''[[The Vicar of Dibley]]'' featuring [[Dawn French]].\n* Premiere of the video for [[Live Lounge Allstars]]' [[Times Like These (Live Lounge Allstars charity single)|cover version]] of Foo Fighter's \"Times Like These\"\n* [[Steve Coogan]] and [[Rob Brydon]] in ''[[The Trip (2010 TV series)|The Trip]]''.\n* [[Catherine Tate]] and [[David Tennant]] perform: \"[[Lauren Cooper|Lauren]] the \u2018[[Am I bovvered|Am I Bovvered]]\u2019 teenager gets home-schooled\"\n* [[Matt Lucas]] and the [[BBC Orchestras and Singers|BBC Orchestra]] perform \"Baked Potato Song\"\n*[[Sam Smith]] performs \"[[Lay Me Down (Sam Smith song)|Lay Me Down]]\"\n*Celeste performs a cover of Bill Withers' \"[[Lean on Me (song)|Lean On Me]]\"\n*[[Jack Whitehall]] in [[Bad Education (TV series)|''Bad Education'']] with [[Mathew Horne|Matthew Horne]] and [[Anthony Joshua]]\n*''[[People Just Do Nothing]]''\n*[[EastEnders]] pub quiz in the [[Queen Vic Fire Week|Queen Vic]] hosted by [[Ian Beale]]\n*[[Peter Kay]] and the British public remake the \"[[(Is This the Way to) Amarillo|Is This the Way to Amarillo]]\" video\n*The first televisual ''[[Little Britain]]'' sketch for over a decade\n*[[Tess Daly]] and [[Claudia Winkleman]] do host a ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]'' choreography challenge\n*[[Romesh Ranganathan]]'s Isolation Diary\n*[[Joe Wicks (coach)|Joe Wicks]]' exercise secrets\n*a reunion of actors who have played the title role in [[Doctor Who]] salute [[National Health Service|NHS]] health workers.\n*Stand-up at home from [[Jason Manford]], [[Rosie Jones (comedian)|Rosie Jones]], [[Tez Ilyas]], [[Dane Baptiste]], [[Russell Kane]], The Lost Voice Guy, [[Nish Kumar]] and more\n*[[Liam Payne]], [[Olly Murs]], [[Leona Lewis]], [[Nicole Scherzinger]], [[Freya Ridings]], [[Katherine Jenkins]], [[Alfie Boe]], [[Gregory Porter]] and more join [[Gary Barlow]] to perform \"[[Sing (Gary Barlow song)|Sing]]\"\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n*{{Official website}}\n*{{BBC programme}}\n*{{IMDb title|tt12183158}}\n<!--\n{{Children in Need}}\n{{Comic Relief}} please wait until after broadcast, so we can make best use of 'what links here' -->\n\n[[Category:Telethons]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Children in Need]]\n[[Category:Comic Relief]]\n[[Category:BBC Television programmes]]\n[[Category:British telethons]]\n[[Category:2020 in British television]]\n[[Category:2020 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:2020 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Charity events in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Responses to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "HeyitsBen", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLine-up:clash", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Big_Night_In"}
{"title_page": "1st Luftwaffe Field Division", "text_new": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name  = 1st ''Luftwaffe'' Field Division\n|image      =\n|caption    =\n|dates      = 1942 \u2013 1944\n|country={{flag|Nazi Germany}}\n|branch     = {{Luftwaffe}}\n|type       =[[Infantry]]\n|role       =\n|size       = [[Division (military)|Division]]\n|battles    = [[World War II]]\n*[[Leningrad\u2013Novgorod Offensive]]\n}}\nThe '''1st ''Luftwaffe'' Field Division''' ({{lang-de|1. Luftwaffen-Feld-Division}}) was an infantry division of the [[Luftwaffe]] branch of the [[Wehrmacht]] that fought in World War II. It was formed using surplus ground crew of the ''Luftwaffe'' and served on the [[Eastern Front (WWII)|Eastern Front]] from late 1942 to early 1944 at which time it was disbanded.\n\n==Operational history==\n{{command structure\n|name= Order of Battle, 1st ''Luftwaffe'' Field Division{{sfn|Mitcham|2007a|pp=299\u2013300}}\n|date=June/July 1942\n|parent=\n|subordinate=\n*I Field ''Jager'' Battalion\n*II Field ''Jager'' Battalion\n*III Field ''Jager'' Battalion\n*IV Field ''Jager'' Battalion\n*1st Luftwaffe Field Artillery Battalion\n*1st Luftwaffe Field Bicycle Company\n*1st Luftwaffe Field Tank Destroyer Battalion\n*1st Luftwaffe Field Engineer Battalion\n*1st Luftwaffe Field Signal Company\n*1st Luftwaffe Field Flak Battalion\n*1st Luftwaffe Field Divisional Supply Troops\n}}\nThe 1st ''Luftwaffe'' Field Division, the first of several [[Luftwaffe Field Division|such divisions]], was formed in mid-1942 in [[K\u00f6nigsberg|K\u00f6nigsberg, Eastern Prussia]], under the command of ''[[Oberst]]''{{#tag:ref|The rank of ''Oberst'' is equivalent to that of [[colonel]] in the United States Army.{{sfn|Mitcham|2007b|p=197}}|group=Note}} [[Gustav Wilke]]. Intended to serve as infantry, its personnel were largely drawn from surplus ''Luftwaffe'' (German Air Force) ground crew. The division included four battalions of infantry, as well as artillery, engineer and signal units although it lacked regimental staff. After training was completed in December 1942 it was sent to [[Army Group North]] as part of the [[18th Army (Wehrmacht)|18th Army]] although still under ''Luftwaffe'' command. Stationed near [[Novgorod]], it was transferred to the [[German Army (Wehrmacht)|Army]] in December 1943. The division saw little fighting until the withdrawal from [[Leningrad]] in January 1944 during which it was involved in [[Leningrad\u2013Novgorod Offensive|heavy defensive battles]] north of Novgorod.{{sfn|Mitcham|2007a|pp=299\u2013300}}\n\nThe division's personnel were inadequately trained for its role as infantry and due to the heavy losses incurred in the Soviet attacks of the 1943/1944 winter, the division itself was disbanded shortly afterwards. Its surviving personnel were absorbed by the [[28th J\u00e4ger Division (Wehrmacht)|28th ''Jager'' Division]].{{sfn|Mitcham|2007a|pp=299\u2013300}}\n\n==Commanders==\n*''Oberst'' [[Gustav Wilke]] (30 September 1942 \u2013 16 January 1943; 14 April \u2013 14 June 1943; 23 July \u2014 30 September 1943);\n*''[[Generalmajor]]''{{#tag:ref|The rank of ''generalmajor'' is equivalent to that of [[brigadier general]] in the United States Army.{{sfn|Mitcham|2007b|p=197}}|group=Note}} Werner Zech (17 January \u2013 13 April 1943);\n*''Oberst'' Anton Longin (15 June \u2013 22 July 1943);\n*''Generalmajor'' Rudolf Petrauschke (1 October 1943 \u2013 February 1944).{{sfn|Mitcham|2007a|pp=299\u2013300}}{{#tag:ref|Ranks stated are those at the time of taking command.{{sfn|Mitcham|2007a|pp=299\u2013300}}|group=Note}}\n\n==Notes==\n;Footnotes\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n;Citations\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Mitcham |first=Samuel W.|author-link=Samuel W. Mitcham|title=German Order of Battle, Volume Two: 291st\u2013999th Infantry Divisions, Named Infantry Divisions, and Special Divisions in WWII|year=2007a|location=Mechanicsburg, PA, United States|publisher=Stackpole Books|isbn=978-0-8117-3437-0|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Mitcham |first=Samuel W.|author-link=Samuel W. Mitcham|title=German Order of Battle, Volume Three: Panzer, Panzer Grenadier, and Waffen SS Divisions in WWII|year=2007b|location=Mechanicsburg, PA, United States|publisher=Stackpole Books|isbn=978-0-8117-3438-7|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Luftwaffe Field Divisions}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n\n[[Category:Luftwaffe Field Divisions|01]]\n[[Category:1942 establishments in Germany]]\n[[Category:1944 disestablishments in Germany]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1942]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1944]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name  = 1st ''Luftwaffe'' Field Division\n|image      =\n|caption    =\n|dates      = 1942 \u2013 1944\n|country={{flag|Nazi Germany}}\n|branch     = {{Luftwaffe}}\n|type       =[[Infantry]]\n|role       =\n|size       = [[Division (military)|Division]]\n|battles    = [[World War II]]\n*[[Leningrad\u2013Novgorod Offensive]]\n}}\nThe '''1st ''Luftwaffe'' Field Division''' ({{lang-de|1. Luftwaffen-Feld-Division}}) was an infantry division of the [[Luftwaffe]] branch of the [[Wehrmacht]] that fought in World War II. It was formed using surplus ground crew of the ''Luftwaffe'' and served on the [[Eastern Front (WWII)|Eastern Front]] from late 1942 to early 1944 at which time it was disbanded.\n\n==Operational history==\n{{command structure\n|name= Order of Battle, 1st ''Luftwaffe'' Field Division{{sfn|Mitcham|2007a|pp=299\u2013300}}\n|date=June/July 1942\n|parent=\n|subordinate=\n*I Field ''Jager'' Battalion\n*II Field ''Jager'' Battalion\n*III Field ''Jager'' Battalion\n*IV Field ''Jager'' Battalion\n*1st Luftwaffe Field Artillery Battalion\n*1st Luftwaffe Field Bicycle Company\n*1st Luftwaffe Field Tank Destroyer Battalion\n*1st Luftwaffe Field Engineer Battalion\n*1st Luftwaffe Field Signal Company\n*1st Luftwaffe Field Flak Battalion\n*1st Luftwaffe Field Divisional Supply Troops\n}}\nThe 1st ''Luftwaffe'' Field Division, the first of several [[Luftwaffe Field Division|such divisions]], was formed in mid-1942 in [[K\u00f6nigsberg|K\u00f6nigsberg, Eastern Prussia]], under the command of ''[[Oberst]]''{{#tag:ref|The rank of ''Oberst'' is equivalent to that of [[colonel]] in the United States Army.{{sfn|Mitcham|2007b|p=197}}|group=Note}} [[Gustav Wilke]]. Intended to serve as infantry, its personnel were largely drawn from surplus ''Luftwaffe'' (German Air Force) ground crew. The division included four battalions of infantry, as well as artillery, engineer and signal units although it lacked a regimental staff. After training was completed in December 1942 it was sent to [[Army Group North]] as part of the [[18th Army (Wehrmacht)|18th Army]] although still under ''Luftwaffe'' command. Stationed near [[Novgorod]], it was transferred to the [[German Army (Wehrmacht)|Army]] in December 1943. The division saw little fighting until the withdrawal from [[Leningrad]] in January 1944 during which it was involved in [[Leningrad\u2013Novgorod Offensive|heavy defensive battles]] north of Novgorod.{{sfn|Mitcham|2007a|pp=299\u2013300}}\n\nThe division's personnel were inadequately trained for its role as infantry and due to the heavy losses incurred in the Soviet attacks of the 1943/1944 winter, the division itself was disbanded shortly afterwards. Its surviving personnel were absorbed by the [[28th J\u00e4ger Division (Wehrmacht)|28th ''Jager'' Division]].{{sfn|Mitcham|2007a|pp=299\u2013300}}\n\n==Commanders==\n*''Oberst'' [[Gustav Wilke]] (30 September 1942 \u2013 16 January 1943; 14 April \u2013 14 June 1943; 23 July \u2014 30 September 1943);\n*''[[Generalmajor]]''{{#tag:ref|The rank of ''generalmajor'' is equivalent to that of [[brigadier general]] in the United States Army.{{sfn|Mitcham|2007b|p=197}}|group=Note}} Werner Zech (17 January \u2013 13 April 1943);\n*''Oberst'' Anton Longin (15 June \u2013 22 July 1943);\n*''Generalmajor'' Rudolf Petrauschke (1 October 1943 \u2013 February 1944).{{sfn|Mitcham|2007a|pp=299\u2013300}}{{#tag:ref|Ranks stated are those at the time of taking command.{{sfn|Mitcham|2007a|pp=299\u2013300}}|group=Note}}\n\n==Notes==\n;Footnotes\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n;Citations\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Mitcham |first=Samuel W.|author-link=Samuel W. Mitcham|title=German Order of Battle, Volume Two: 291st\u2013999th Infantry Divisions, Named Infantry Divisions, and Special Divisions in WWII|year=2007a|location=Mechanicsburg, PA, United States|publisher=Stackpole Books|isbn=978-0-8117-3437-0|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Mitcham |first=Samuel W.|author-link=Samuel W. Mitcham|title=German Order of Battle, Volume Three: Panzer, Panzer Grenadier, and Waffen SS Divisions in WWII|year=2007b|location=Mechanicsburg, PA, United States|publisher=Stackpole Books|isbn=978-0-8117-3438-7|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Luftwaffe Field Divisions}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n\n[[Category:Luftwaffe Field Divisions|01]]\n[[Category:1942 establishments in Germany]]\n[[Category:1944 disestablishments in Germany]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1942]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1944]]\n", "name_user": "LucasA04", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOperational history:Spelling/grammar/punctuation/typographical correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1st_Luftwaffe_Field_Division"}
{"title_page": "Sangeet Samrat Tansen", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Sangeet Samrat Tansen \n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| caption        = \n| director       = S. N. Tripathi\n| producer       = Sur Singar Chitra\n| writer         = \n| narrator       = \n| starring       = [[Bharat Bhushan]]<br>[[Anita Guha]]<br>[[David (actor)|David]]<br>[[Sapru (actor)|Sapru]]<br />[[Mukri]]\n| music          = [[S. N. Tripathi]]\n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| distributor    =\n| studio         = Sur Singar Chitra \n| released       = 1962\n| runtime        = 170 min\n| country        = [[India]]\n| language       = [[Hindi]]\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n| preceded_by    = \n| followed_by    = \n| website        = \n}}\n'''''Sangeet Samrat Tansen''''' (King of Music- Tansen) is a [[List of Bollywood films of 1962|1962]] [[Hindi]] biopic historical drama film directed by S. N. Tripathi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gomolo.com/sangeet-samrat-tansen-movie/3407|title=Sangeet Samrat Tansen|publisher=Gomolo.com|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"RajadhyakshaWillemen2014\">{{cite book|author1=Ashish Rajadhyaksha|author2=Paul Willemen|author3=Professor of Critical Studies Paul Willemen|title=Encyclopedia of Indian Cinema|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SLkABAAAQBAJ&pg=PT301|accessdate=29 October 2014|date=10 July 2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-94318-9|pages=301\u2013}}</ref> Produced by Sur Singar Chitra it had lyrics by [[Shailendra (lyricist)|Shailendra]] and [[Swami Haridas]] with music by [[S. N. Tripathi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lyricsbogie.com/category/movies/sangeet-samrat-tansen-1962|title=Sangeet Samrat Tansen|publisher=Lyricsbogie.com|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> One of the popular songs from this film was \"Jhoomti Chali Hawaa\" in [[Raga Sohni]], sung by [[Mukesh (singer)|Mukesh]] for [[Bharat Bhushan]].<ref name=Mukesh>{{cite web|title=Mukesh Classical List|url=http://www.singermukesh.com/list/classical.htm|website=singermukesh.com|publisher=SingerMukesh.com|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=Raheja>{{cite web|last1=Raheja|first1=Dinesh|title=Bharat Bhushan The Tragic Hero -Famous Songs|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2003/apr/22dinesh.htm|website=rediff.com|publisher=Rediff.com|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> The film starred [[Bharat Bhushan]], [[Anita Guha]], Sabita Chatterjee, [[David (actor)|David]], [[Sapru (actor)|Sapru]] and [[Mukri]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citwf.com/film304760.htm|title=Sangeet Samrat Tansen|publisher=Alan Goble|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe story is a biopic of the famous court singer musician, Mian [[Tansen]], one of the [[Navaratnas]] in [[Emperor Akbar]]\u2019s court.<ref name=\"Chakravarty2011\">{{cite book|author=Sumita S. Chakravarty|title=National Identity in Indian Popular Cinema, 1947-1987|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l8T0uwJtMxkC&pg=PA168|accessdate=29 October 2014|date=18 May 2011|publisher=University of Texas Press|isbn=978-0-292-78985-2|pages=168\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nTansen, called Ramtanu or Tanu is born dumb, but a miracle in the temple at the age five gives the boy the ability to speak and sing. His voice attracts the sage musician [[Swami Haridas]] of [[Brindaban]]. He trains the boy in the [[Dhrupad]] style. Swami Haridas gets Tanu to study under [[Muhammad Ghaus]], where he lives with his childhood mate Hansa. Several years pass and Ghaus asks Tanu to shift to the court of Raja Ramchandra. This disappoints Tanu as he has plans to marry Hansa. However, he ventures forth to the palace where his voice is applauded and he is awarded the title of Sangeet Shiromani Tansen. His singing reputation reaches Emperor Akbar, who invites him to join his court singers. There, he becomes one of the nine jewels of the Emperor's exceptionally talented men. The story then follows misunderstandings with his beloved Hansa, his singing prowess and finally his getting united once again with Hansa.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Bharat Bhushan]] as [[Tansen|Sangeet Shiromani / Sangeet Samrat Tansen 'Tanu']]\n* [[Anita Guha]] as Hansa\n* [[Mukri]] as Ustad Fateh Khan\n* [[David (actor)|David Abraham]] as [[Muhammad Ghaus|Mohammed Khauj]] \n* [[Sapru (actor)|D. K. Sapru]] as Raja Ramchandra\n* Sabita Chatterjee as Naaz Praveen\n* Kumar\n* Prem Sagar\n* Parshuram\n* Radheshyam\n* [[S. N. Tripathi]] as Akbar (uncredited)\n\n==Tansen In Films==\nTwo films were made depicting the life of Tansen. The first was the [[K. L. Saigal]] starrer ''[[Tansen (film)|Tansen]]'' (1943) with [[Khursheed Bano]] which had popular songs and was a success at the box-office. The second was ''Sangeet Samrat Tansen''.<ref name=\"PTI\">{{cite book|title=India Perspectives|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QKqyAAAAIAAJ|accessdate=29 October 2014|year=2002|publisher=Produced by PTI for the Ministry of External Affairs}}</ref> Tansen, played by [[Surendra (actor)|Surendra]], was also shown in ''[[Baiju Bawra (film)|Baiju Bawra]]'' (1952), where he competes with Baiju in a music competition only to lose to him.<ref name=\"AsianMusic\">{{cite book|title=Asian Music: Journal of the Society for Asian Music|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ni8JAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=29 October 2014|year=2005|publisher=The Society}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\nS. N. Tripathi, along with directing the film also gave the music direction, and enacted the part of Emperor Akbar.. The lyrics were by Shailendra and Swami Haridas, who is the author of \"Sapta Suran Teen Gram\" sung in [[Raga Yaman]] Kalyan (or Adbhut Kalyan).<ref>{{cite web|url= http://myswar.com/album/sangeet-samrat-tansen-1962|title=Sangeet Samrat Tansen|publisher=MySwar.com|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mishraraag.blogspot.in/2012/01/tansens-grooming-in-music.html |title=Tansen's Grooming in Music|publisher=Mishraraag|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> Some of the Raga-based songs: The song  \"Raag Bhairav Pratham Shant Ras\" shows the completion of Tansen's training by Haridas by his singing the raagmala, \"Deepak Jalao Jyoti Jagao\" in Raaga Dipak and \"traditionally associated with fire\",<ref name=\"AsianMusic\"/>\n\"Badli Badli Duniya Hai Meri\" in Raag Jhinjhoti sung by Lata Mangeshkar and Mahendra Kapoor,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chandrakantha.com/raga_raag/film_song_raga/jhinjhoti.shtml|title=Film Song Raga|publisher=Chandrakantha.com|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> and \"Jhoomti Chali Hawaa\" in Raaga Sohni sung by Mukesh.<ref name=\"Mukesh\" />\n\n===Songlist===\n{| border=\"4\" cellpadding=\"7\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! # !! Title !! Singer !! Lyricist\n|-\n| 1\n| \"Sapta Suran Teen Gram\"\n| [[Manna Dey]]\n| [[Swami Haridas]]\n|-\n| 2\n| \"Raag Bhairav Pratham Shant Ras Jake\"\n| Manna Dey\n| Swami Haridas\n|-\n| 3\n| \"Badli Badli Duniya Hai Meri\" (Duet)\n| [[Lata Mangeshkar]], [[Mahendra Kapoor]]\n| [[Shailendra (lyricist)|Shailendra]]\n|-\n| 4\n| \"Sakhi Kaise Dharoon Main Dhir\"\n| Lata Mangeshkar\n| Shailendra\n|-\n| 5\n| \"Kantadha Kantadha\"\n| Manna Dey\n| Shailendra\n|-\n| 6\n| \"Jhoomti Chali Hawa\"\n| [[Mukesh (singer)|Mukesh]]\n| Shailendra\n|-\n| 7\n| \"Mitwa Laut Aaye Meri\"\n| Manna Dey\n| Shailendra\n|-\n| 8\n| \"Sudh Bisar Gayi Aaj\"\n| Manna Dey, [[Mohammed Rafi]]\n| Shailendra\n|-\n| 9\n| \"Deepak Jalao Jyoti Jagao\"\n| Mohammed Rafi\n| Shailendra\n|-\n| 10\n| \"Meha aao re Ghir Ghir Ke Chaon re\"\n| Lata Mangeshkar, Manna Dey, Asha Bhonsle\n| Shailendra\n|-\n| 11\n| \"Hey Natraj Gangadhar Shambu\"\n| Kamal Barot, Mahendra Kapoor\n| Shailendra\n|-\n| 12\n| \"Log Jaage Pavan Jaage\"\n|\n| Shailendra\n|-\n| 13\n| \"Kuhoo Kuhoo Pi Kahan\"\n|\n| Shailendra\n|-\n| 14\n| \"Yeh Jahaan Hai Teri Kudrat\"\n|\n| Shailendra\n|-\n| 15\n| \"Toot Gayi Mere Man Ki Bina Toot Gayi\"\n| Poorna Seth, Pandharinath Kolhapure\n| Shailendra\n|-\n| 16\n| \"Badli Duniya Hai Meri\" (Female)\n| Lata Mangeshkar\n| Shailendra\n|-\n| 17\n| \"Tu hai ke nahin hai\"\n| Manna Dey and Mohd. Rafi\n| Shailendra\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id =0368239 |title =Sangeet Samrat Tansen (1962) }}\n*[http://www.pandharinathkolhapure.com/Concert.html Pandharinath Kolhapure]\n\n[[Category:1962 films]]\n[[Category:1960s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian epic films]]\n[[Category:Films set in the Mughal Empire]]\n[[Category:1960s historical films]]\n[[Category:1960s biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by S. N. Tripathi]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about musicians]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Tansen]]\n[[Category:Indian biographical drama films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Sangeet Samrat Tansen \n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| caption        = \n| director       = S. N. Tripathi\n| producer       = Sur Singar Chitra\n| writer         = \n| narrator       = \n| starring       = [[Bharat Bhushan]]<br>[[Anita Guha]]<br>[[David (actor)|David]]<br>[[Sapru (actor)|Sapru]]<br />[[Mukri]]\n| music          = [[S. N. Tripathi]]\n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| distributor    =\n| studio         = Sur Singar Chitra \n| released       = 1962\n| runtime        = 170 min\n| country        = [[India]]\n| language       = [[Hindi]]\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n| preceded_by    = \n| followed_by    = \n| website        = \n}}\n'''''Sangeet Samrat Tansen''''' (King of Music- Tansen) is a [[List of Bollywood films of 1962|1962]] [[Hindi]] biopic historical drama film directed by S. N. Tripathi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gomolo.com/sangeet-samrat-tansen-movie/3407|title=Sangeet Samrat Tansen|publisher=Gomolo.com|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"RajadhyakshaWillemen2014\">{{cite book|author1=Ashish Rajadhyaksha|author2=Paul Willemen|author3=Professor of Critical Studies Paul Willemen|title=Encyclopedia of Indian Cinema|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SLkABAAAQBAJ&pg=PT301|accessdate=29 October 2014|date=10 July 2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-94318-9|pages=301\u2013}}</ref> Produced by Sur Singar Chitra it had lyrics by [[Shailendra (lyricist)|Shailendra]] and [[Swami Haridas]] with music by [[S. N. Tripathi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lyricsbogie.com/category/movies/sangeet-samrat-tansen-1962|title=Sangeet Samrat Tansen|publisher=Lyricsbogie.com|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> One of the popular songs from this film was \"Jhoomti Chali Hawaa\" in [[Raga Sohni]], sung by [[Mukesh (singer)|Mukesh]] for [[Bharat Bhushan]].<ref name=Mukesh>{{cite web|title=Mukesh Classical List|url=http://www.singermukesh.com/list/classical.htm|website=singermukesh.com|publisher=SingerMukesh.com|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=Raheja>{{cite web|last1=Raheja|first1=Dinesh|title=Bharat Bhushan The Tragic Hero -Famous Songs|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2003/apr/22dinesh.htm|website=rediff.com|publisher=Rediff.com|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> The film starred [[Bharat Bhushan]], [[Anita Guha]], Sabita Chatterjee, [[David (actor)|David]], [[Sapru (actor)|Sapru]] and [[Mukri]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citwf.com/film304760.htm|title=Sangeet Samrat Tansen|publisher=Alan Goble|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe story is a biopic of the famous court singer musician, Mian [[Tansen]], one of the [[Navaratnas]] in [[Emperor Akbar]]\u2019s court.<ref name=\"Chakravarty2011\">{{cite book|author=Sumita S. Chakravarty|title=National Identity in Indian Popular Cinema, 1947-1987|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l8T0uwJtMxkC&pg=PA168|accessdate=29 October 2014|date=18 May 2011|publisher=University of Texas Press|isbn=978-0-292-78985-2|pages=168\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nTansen, called Ramtanu or Tanu is born dumb, but a miracle in the temple at the age five gives the boy the ability to speak and sing. His voice attracts the sage musician [[Swami Haridas]] of [[Brindaban]]. He trains the boy in the [[Dhrupad]] style. Swami Haridas gets Tanu to study under [[Muhammad Ghaus]], where he lives with his childhood mate Hansa. Several years pass and Ghaus asks Tanu to shift to the court of Raja Ramchandra. This disappoints Tanu as he has plans to marry Hansa. However, he ventures forth to the palace where his voice is applauded and he is awarded the title of Sangeet Shiromani Tansen. His singing reputation reaches Emperor Akbar, who invites him to join his court singers. There, he becomes one of the nine jewels of the Emperor's exceptionally talented men. The story then follows misunderstandings with his beloved Hansa, his singing prowess and finally his getting united once again with Hansa.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Bharat Bhushan]] as [[Tansen|Sangeet Shiromani / Sangeet Samrat Tansen 'Tanu']]\n* [[Anita Guha]] as Hansa\n* [[Mukri]] as Ustad Fateh Khan\n* [[David (actor)|David Abraham]] as [[Muhammad Ghaus|Mohammed Khauj]] \n* [[Sapru (actor)|D. K. Sapru]] as Raja Ramchandra\n* Sabita Chatterjee as Naaz Praveen\n* Kumar\n* Prem Sagar\n* Parshuram\n* Radheshyam\n* [[S. N. Tripathi]] as Akbar (uncredited)\n\n==Tansen In Films==\nTwo films were made depicting the life of Tansen. The first was the [[K. L. Saigal]] starrer ''[[Tansen (film)|Tansen]]'' (1943) with [[Khursheed Bano]] which had popular songs and was a success at the box-office. The second was ''Sangeet Samrat Tansen''.<ref name=\"PTI\">{{cite book|title=India Perspectives|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QKqyAAAAIAAJ|accessdate=29 October 2014|year=2002|publisher=Produced by PTI for the Ministry of External Affairs}}</ref> Tansen, played by [[Surendra (actor)|Surendra]], was also shown in ''[[Baiju Bawra (film)|Baiju Bawra]]'' (1952), where he competes with Baiju in a music competition only to lose to him.<ref name=\"AsianMusic\">{{cite book|title=Asian Music: Journal of the Society for Asian Music|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ni8JAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=29 October 2014|year=2005|publisher=The Society}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\nS. N. Tripathi, along with directing the film also gave the music direction. The lyrics were by Shailendra and Swami Haridas, who is the author of \"Sapta Suran Teen Gram\" sung in [[Raga Yaman]] Kalyan (or Adbhut Kalyan).<ref>{{cite web|url= http://myswar.com/album/sangeet-samrat-tansen-1962|title=Sangeet Samrat Tansen|publisher=MySwar.com|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mishraraag.blogspot.in/2012/01/tansens-grooming-in-music.html |title=Tansen's Grooming in Music|publisher=Mishraraag|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> Some of the Raga-based songs: The song  \"Raag Bhairav Pratham Shant Ras\" shows the completion of Tansen's training by Haridas by his singing the raagmala, \"Deepak Jalao Jyoti Jagao\" in Raaga Dipak and \"traditionally associated with fire\",<ref name=\"AsianMusic\"/>\n\"Badli Badli Duniya Hai Meri\" in Raag Jhinjhoti sung by Lata Mangeshkar and Mahendra Kapoor,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chandrakantha.com/raga_raag/film_song_raga/jhinjhoti.shtml|title=Film Song Raga|publisher=Chandrakantha.com|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> and \"Jhoomti Chali Hawaa\" in Raaga Sohni sung by Mukesh.<ref name=\"Mukesh\" />\n\n===Songlist===\n{| border=\"4\" cellpadding=\"7\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! # !! Title !! Singer !! Lyricist\n|-\n| 1\n| \"Sapta Suran Teen Gram\"\n| [[Manna Dey]]\n| [[Swami Haridas]]\n|-\n| 2\n| \"Raag Bhairav Pratham Shant Ras Jake\"\n| Manna Dey\n| Swami Haridas\n|-\n| 3\n| \"Badli Badli Duniya Hai Meri\" (Duet)\n| [[Lata Mangeshkar]], [[Mahendra Kapoor]]\n| [[Shailendra (lyricist)|Shailendra]]\n|-\n| 4\n| \"Sakhi Kaise Dharoon Main Dhir\"\n| Lata Mangeshkar\n| Shailendra\n|-\n| 5\n| \"Kantadha Kantadha\"\n| Manna Dey\n| Shailendra\n|-\n| 6\n| \"Jhoomti Chali Hawa\"\n| [[Mukesh (singer)|Mukesh]]\n| Shailendra\n|-\n| 7\n| \"Mitwa Laut Aaye Meri\"\n| Manna Dey\n| Shailendra\n|-\n| 8\n| \"Sudh Bisar Gayi Aaj\"\n| Manna Dey, [[Mohammed Rafi]]\n| Shailendra\n|-\n| 9\n| \"Deepak Jalao Jyoti Jagao\"\n| Mohammed Rafi\n| Shailendra\n|-\n| 10\n| \"Meha aao re Ghir Ghir Ke Chaon re\"\n| Lata Mangeshkar, Manna Dey, Asha Bhonsle\n| Shailendra\n|-\n| 11\n| \"Hey Natraj Gangadhar Shambu\"\n| Kamal Barot, Mahendra Kapoor\n| Shailendra\n|-\n| 12\n| \"Log Jaage Pavan Jaage\"\n|\n| Shailendra\n|-\n| 13\n| \"Kuhoo Kuhoo Pi Kahan\"\n|\n| Shailendra\n|-\n| 14\n| \"Yeh Jahaan Hai Teri Kudrat\"\n|\n| Shailendra\n|-\n| 15\n| \"Toot Gayi Mere Man Ki Bina Toot Gayi\"\n| Poorna Seth, Pandharinath Kolhapure\n| Shailendra\n|-\n| 16\n| \"Badli Duniya Hai Meri\" (Female)\n| Lata Mangeshkar\n| Shailendra\n|-\n| 17\n| \"Tu hai ke nahin hai\"\n| Manna Dey and Mohd. Rafi\n| Shailendra\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id =0368239 |title =Sangeet Samrat Tansen (1962) }}\n*[http://www.pandharinathkolhapure.com/Concert.html Pandharinath Kolhapure]\n\n[[Category:1962 films]]\n[[Category:1960s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian epic films]]\n[[Category:Films set in the Mughal Empire]]\n[[Category:1960s historical films]]\n[[Category:1960s biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by S. N. Tripathi]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about musicians]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Tansen]]\n[[Category:Indian biographical drama films]]\n", "name_user": "Srirangam99", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSoundtrack", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sangeet_Samrat_Tansen"}
{"title_page": "Jessica Walsh", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Jessica Walsh\n| image = Jessica Walsh 2013.jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1986|10|30}}\n| birth_place = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[Americans|American]]\n| alma_mater = [[Rhode Island School of Design]] (BFA, 2008)\n| other_names =\n| known_for =\n| religion =\n| occupation = Art director & partner, <br/> Sagmeister & Walsh\n| years_active = 2008-present\n| spouse =\n| children =\n| website = {{URL|https://andwalsh.com/|andwalsh.com}} \n}}\n\n'''Jessica Walsh''' (born October 30, 1986)<ref name=\"cdover\">Caitlin Dover, [http://blogs.guggenheim.org/checklist/awesome-twisted-beautiful-qa-designer-jessica-walsh/ \u201c'Awesome, Twisted, and Beautiful': A Q&A with Designer Jessica Walsh,\u201d] [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum|Guggenheim Blog]], February 7, 2014.</ref> is an American graphic designer, art director and illustrator, and founder of creative agency & Walsh.\n\n==Early life and education==\nWalsh was born in [[New York (state)|New York]]<ref>Ryan & Tina Essmaker, [https://thegreatdiscontent.com/jessica-walsh \u201cJessica Walsh,\u201d] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140521070210/https://thegreatdiscontent.com/jessica-walsh |date=2014-05-21 }} The Great Discontent, September 18, 2012.</ref> and raised in nearby [[Ridgefield, Connecticut]].<ref name=\"cdover\"/> She began coding and designing websites at age 11<ref name=\"srodd\">Scott Rodd, [http://observer.com/2014/04/jessica-walsh-graphic-designer-profile/#axzz324bfL7ST \u201cFont of Youth: Jessica Walsh, Graphic Design\u2019s \u2018It\u2019 Girl,\u201d] ''[[New York Observer]]'', April 10, 2014.</ref> and went on to study graphic design at the [[Rhode Island School of Design]] (RISD).<ref name=\"lmallonee\">Laura C. Mallonee, [http://scenemag.com/2014/05/jessica-walsh-art-director-of-sagmeister-walsh/ \u201cJessica Walsh: Art Director of Sagmeister & Walsh,\u201d] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160514171322/http://scenemag.com/2014/05/jessica-walsh-art-director-of-sagmeister-walsh/ |date=2016-05-14 }} ''Scene'' magazine, May 2014.</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Sagmeister & Walsh===\nAfter earning her Bachelor of Fine Arts from RISD in 2008, Walsh moved to [[New York City]]. to intern at the notable design firm [[Pentagram (design studio)|Pentagram]]. She turned down a job at Apple where she was offered nearly $100,000 annually to accept the internship under Paula Scher at Pentagram, where she would stay for nearly a year.<ref name=\"srodd\"/><ref name=\"aallsopp\">Ashleigh Allsopp, [http://www.digitalartsonline.co.uk/news/illustration/interview-jessica-walsh-talks-upcoming-projects-favourite-designs-naked-photo/ \u201cInterview: Jessica Walsh discusses play, her favourite designs, future plans & that photo,\u201d] Digital Arts, May 9, 2013.</ref> She then worked as an associate art director at ''[[Print (magazine)|Print]]'' magazine<ref name=\"aallsopp\"/> and had design work and illustrations featured in various books, magazines and newspapers, including the ''[[New York Times]]'' and ''[[New York Times Magazine]]''.<ref name=\"envyindex\">[http://www.thelmagazine.com/gyrobase/the-envy-index-25-under-25/Content?oid=2196532&storyPage=9 \u201cThe Envy Index: 25 Under 25,\u201d] ''[[The L Magazine]]'', December 7, 2011.</ref><ref name=\"sgruenwedel\">Stefan Gruenwedel, [http://www.adobe.com/inspire/2012/12/interview-jessica-walsh.html \u201cHand-crafted photo illustrations of Jessica Walsh,\u201d] [[adobe.com]], December 2012.</ref> In reflections about her time at Print magazine, she identifies it as one of the best things to happen in her career as it was how she found and developed her personal style.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eyeondesign.aiga.org/the-first-thing-i-ever-designed-how-jessica-walsh-developed-her-distinct-colorful-paper-set-style-at-print/|title=How Jessica Walsh Developed Her Distinct + Colorful Style of Art Direction at Print|last=Morley|first=Madeleine|date=May 29, 2017|website=Eye on Design|access-date=February 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Walsh met [[Stefan Sagmeister]]. He looked through her portfolio and offered her a job at his design studio, Sagmeister Inc.<ref name=\"srodd\"/><ref name=\"lmallonee\"/> In June 2012, after two years at the firm, Walsh was made partner, at age 25.<ref name=\"jedwards\">Jim Edwards, [http://www.businessinsider.com/why-this-new-york-design-agency-makes-its-employees-pose-naked-for-official-staff-photos-2013-5?op=1#!KvyxW \u201cWhy This New York Design Agency Makes Its Employees Pose Naked For Staff Photos,\u201d] ''[[Business Insider]]'', June 2, 2013.</ref><ref>Patrick Burgoyne, [http://www.creativereview.co.uk/cr-blog/2012/june/getting-naked-with-sagmeister \u201cThe perils of getting naked with Sagmeister,\u201d] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140521033248/http://www.creativereview.co.uk/cr-blog/2012/june/getting-naked-with-sagmeister |date=2014-05-21 }} Creative Review, June 1, 2012.</ref> In homage to a nude self-portrait Sagmeister had sent out to announce the formation of his own firm 19 years prior, the new partners released a photo of themselves naked in their office to announce the renaming of the firm to Sagmeister & Walsh.<ref name=\"jedwards\"/>\n\nBlending handcraft, photography and painting with digital design,<ref name=\"cdover\"/><ref>Tina Berglund, [http://radarmagazine.se/people/interview-people/jessica-walsh/ \u201cJessica Walsh,\u201d] ''Radar'', December 4, 2013.</ref> Walsh works primarily on branding, typography, website design and art installations.<ref name=\"sgruenwedel\"/> Her signature style has been described as \"bold, emotional and provocative\"<ref name=\"lmallonee\"/> with the occasional surrealistic flourish,<ref>Laura Neilson, [http://www.wearedesignbureau.com/projects/the-inspiration-issue-jessica-walsh/ \u201cSurrealism,\u201d] ''Design Bureau'', August 29, 2013.</ref> and her art has been said to look \"hand-made and at times quite daring.\"<ref name=\"sgruenwedel\"/> Walsh has worked on projects for clients including [[Levi's]], [[A\u00efshti|Aizone]], [[Adobe Systems|Adobe]] and Colab Eyewear,<ref name=\"srodd\"/><ref>Carey Dunne, [http://www.fastcodesign.com/3027274/innovation-by-design/sagmeister-walsh-compete-in-a-gameshow-to-recreate-adobes-logo \u201cSagmeister & Walsh Compete In A Gameshow To Re-Create Adobe\u2019s Logo,\u201d] ''[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]]'', March 6, 2014.</ref> and rebranding efforts for [[The Jewish Museum of New York]] and the [[Aldrich Contemporary Art Museum]] in Connecticut.<ref name=\"cdover\"/><ref>Carey Dunne, [http://www.fastcodesign.com/3029868/sagmeister-walsh-rebrand-the-jewish-museum-using-sacred-geometry \u201cSagmeister & Walsh Rebrand The Jewish Museum, Using Sacred Geometry,\u201d] ''Fast Company'', April 30, 2014.</ref> Walsh and Sagmeister collaborated on ''Six Things: Sagmeister & Walsh'', an exhibition that opened at the Jewish Museum in March 2013, and ran for five months. For the exhibit, an exploration of happiness, they created a sound-activated sculpture and five short films.<ref>Anna Carnick, [https://tmagazine.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/03/14/six-things-sagmeister-walsh/?_php=true&_type=blogs&action=click&module=Search&region=searchResults&mabReward=relbias%3Ar&url=http%3A%2F%2Fquery.nytimes.com%2Fsearch%2Fsitesearch%2F%3Faction%3Dclick%26region%3DMasthead%26pgtype%3DHomepage%26module%3DSearchSubmit%26contentCollection%3DHomepage%26t%3Dqry319%23%2Fjessica+walsh&_r=0 \u201cSix Things: Sagmeister & Walsh,\u201d] ''[[T: The New York Times Style Magazine]]'', March 14, 2013.</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, Walsh announced she was leaving Sagmeister & Walsh and forming her own studio, & Walsh. Walsh has said that the studio is a fulfillment of her dreams as a teen to run her own business and the studio will become one of 36 female-led creative studios in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adweek.com/agencies/famed-designer-jessica-walsh-starts-her-own-creative-agency/|title=Famed Designer Jessica Walsh Starts Her Own Creative Agency|last=ago|first=Minda Smiley{{!}}6 days|website=www.adweek.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref>\n\n===''40 Days of Dating''===\nIn 2013, Walsh and fellow designer and friend Tim Goodman decided to date for 40 days to see if they could overcome their relationship issues and fall in love. They documented the social experiment on a blog, ''[http://fortydaysofdating.com 40 Days of Dating]'', launched in July 2013.<ref name=\"srodd\"/><ref name=\"mruiz\">Michelle Ruiz, [http://www.cosmopolitan.com/celebrity/exclusive/forty-days-of-dating-interview \u201c40 Days of Dating Couple Endorse Lizzy Caplan, Paul Bettany for Movie Version,\u201d] ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'', September 25, 2013.</ref> In support of the blog, which earned more than 5 million unique visitors in less than a year,<ref name=\"srodd\"/> they appeared in segments on talk shows ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]]''<ref>[http://www.today.com/health/longtime-friends-experiment-date-40-days-8C11111046 \u201cLongtime friends experiment, date for 40 days,\u201d] ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]]'', [[NBC]], September 9, 2013.</ref> and ''[[The View (U.S. TV series)|The View]]''.<ref>''[[The View (U.S. TV series)|The View]]'', [http://abc.go.com/shows/the-view/episode-guide/2013-12/13-friday-dec-13-2013 Season 18, Episode 69], [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], December 13, 2013.</ref> In September 2013, [[Warner Brothers]] purchased the film rights, with a screenplay to be written by [[Lorene Scafaria]], and [[Michael Sucsy]] attached to direct.<ref name=\"edodds\">Eric Dodds, [http://entertainment.time.com/2013/09/19/40-days-online-stars-prepare-for-hollywood-ending/ \u201c\u201940 Days\u2019 Online Stars Prepare for Hollywood Ending,\u201d] ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', September 19, 2013.</ref><ref>Mike Fleming, Jr., [https://www.deadline.com/2013/09/warner-bros-buys-rights-to-40-days-of-dating-blog-michael-sucsy-to-direct-film/ \u201cWarner Bros Buys Rights To \u201940 Days of Dating\u2019 Blog: Michael Sucsy To Direct,\u201d] ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'', September 17, 2013.</ref> Walsh and Goodman will serve as consulting writers on the script<ref name=\"mruiz\"/> and also wrote a book for [[Abrams Books|Abrams]], ''40 Days of Dating: An Experiment'', out in early 2015.<ref name=\"srodd\"/><ref name=\"lmallonee\"/>\n\n=== ''12 Kinds of Kindness'' ===\nIn 2016, Walsh and Goodman began a second project together, which they described as a \"12-step experiment designed to open [their] hearts, eyes, and minds\". They set up twelve tasks in which they displayed kindness to people and recorded the results. The experiment was live from January 13 to March 15, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://12kindsofkindness.com/about/|title=About \u2013 12 Kinds of Kindness|website=12kindsofkindness.com|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref>\n\n=== Ladies Wine and Design ===\nWalsh started Ladies, Wine & Design, a nonprofit organization to encourage women to work together rather than compete, in 2016. {{As of|September 2019}}, the organization has 273 local chapters around the world.<ref name=lwddezeen>{{cite web|url=https://www.dezeen.com/2019/09/27/jessica-walsh-design-interview/|title=Jessica Walsh: Design Interview|first=Bridget|last=Cogley|work=Dezeen|date=September 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Other work===\nWalsh teaches design and typography at the [[School of Visual Arts]] in New York.<ref name=\"msilverberg\">Michael Silverberg, [http://www.printmag.com/featured/some-uncomfortable-thoughts-about-sagmeister-walshs-new-identity/ \u201cSome Uncomfortable Thoughts About Sagmeister & Walsh\u2019s New Identity,\u201d] ''[[Print (magazine)|Print]]'', January 23, 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.sva.edu/faculty/jessica-walsh \u201cOur Faculty: Jessica Walsh,\u201d] sva.edu. Accessed May 20, 2014.</ref> She is represented by [[Creative Artists Agency]].<ref name=\"edodds\"/>\n\n==Exhibitions==\n* ''Sagmeister: Another Show About Advertising and Promotion Materials'', [[Les Arts D\u00e9coratifs]], [[The Louvre]], [[Paris, France]], 2011-12<ref>[http://ndagallery.cooperhewitt.org/gallery/Les-Arts-Decoratifs-Poster/4808685 \u201cLes Arts Decoratifs Poster,\u201d] National Design Awards. Retrieved May 20, 2014.</ref>\n* ''The Happy Show'', [[Institute of Contemporary Art, Philadelphia|Institute of Contemporary Art]], [[Philadelphia, PA]]; [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles|Museum of Contemporary Art]], [[Los Angeles, CA]]; [[Chicago Cultural Center]], [[Chicago, IL]]; [[Design Exchange]], [[Toronto]], [[Canada]], 2012<ref name=\"klala\">Kisa Lala, [https://www.huffingtonpost.com/kisa-lala/moving-against-type-stefan-sagmeister_b_3321523.html \u201cMoving Against Type: Stefan Sagmeister,\u201d] ''[[Huffington Post]]'', June 19, 2013.</ref>\n* ''Six Things: Sagmeister & Walsh'', [[The Jewish Museum of New York|The Jewish Museum]], [[New York, NY]], 2013<ref name=\"klala\"/>\n*''Sagmeister & Walsh: Beauty'', [[Museum of Applied Arts, Vienna|MAK \u2013 Museum of Applied Arts Vienna]], 2018/2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mak.at/en_sagmeister_walsh|title=Exhibition Sagmeister & Walsh: Beauty - MAK Museum Vienna|website=www.mak.at|language=en|access-date=2018-10-25}}</ref>\n\n==Honors and awards==\n* New Star of Design, ''Computer Arts'', 2010<ref>[http://www.creativebloq.com/computer-arts/new-stars-design-12098950 \u201cThe new stars of design,\u201d] ''Computer Arts'', December 15, 2009.</ref>\n* Society of Publication Designers award, 2010<ref name=\"sgruenwedel\"/>\n* Young Gun Award, [[Art Directors Club of New York|Art Directors Club]], 2011<ref name=\"gdusa\">[http://www.gdusa.com/issue_2013/january/ptw/jessica-walsh.php \u201cPeople to Watch: Jessica Walsh,\u201d] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140521032859/http://www.gdusa.com/issue_2013/january/ptw/jessica-walsh.php |date=2014-05-21 }} ''GD USA'', January 2013.</ref>\n* New Visual Artist Award, ''[[Print (magazine)|Print]]'' magazine, 2011<ref name=\"msilverberg\"/>\n* The Envy Index: 25 Under 25, ''[[The L Magazine]]'', 2011<ref name=\"envyindex\"/> \n* Type Director\u2019s Club Award, [[Les Arts D\u00e9coratifs]] poster, 2012<ref name=\"sgruenwedel\"/>\n* 25 People Shaping the Future of Design, ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'', 2013<ref>Emily Anne Kuriyama, [http://www.complex.com/art-design/2013/10/future-of-design/stefan-sagmeister-jessica-walsh \u201c25 People Shaping the Future of Design,\u201d] ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'', October 14, 2013.</ref>\n* People to Watch, ''GD USA'', 2013<ref name=\"gdusa\"/>\n* [[Webby Award]], Best Home/Welcome Page, Sagmeister & Walsh, 2014<ref>Abigail Tracy, [http://www.inc.com/abigail-tracy/webby-awards-name-best-of-the-internet.html \u201cWebby Awards Honor the Best of the Internet,\u201d] ''[[Inc. (magazine)|Inc.]]'', April 28, 2014.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWalsh lives in New York City with her husband, cinematographer Zak Mulligan.<ref name=\"srodd\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.sagmeisterwalsh.com/ Sagmeister & Walsh website]\n* [http://fortydaysofdating.com/ ''40 Days of Dating'' blog]\n*[http://www.12kindsofkindness.com www.12kindsofkindness.com]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walsh, Jessica}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American graphic designers]]\n[[Category:Women graphic designers]]\n[[Category:Rhode Island School of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:School of Visual Arts faculty]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York City]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Jessica Walsh\n| image = Jessica Walsh 2013.jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1986|10|30}}\n| birth_place = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[Americans|American]]\n| alma_mater = [[Rhode Island School of Design]] (BFA, 2008)\n| other_names =\n| known_for =\n| religion =\n| occupation = Art director & partner, <br/> Sagmeister & Walsh\n| years_active = 2008-present\n| spouse =\n| children =\n| website = {{URL|http://www.sagmeisterwalsh.com/|sagmeisterwalsh.com}} \n}}\n\n'''Jessica Walsh''' (born October 30, 1986)<ref name=\"cdover\">Caitlin Dover, [http://blogs.guggenheim.org/checklist/awesome-twisted-beautiful-qa-designer-jessica-walsh/ \u201c'Awesome, Twisted, and Beautiful': A Q&A with Designer Jessica Walsh,\u201d] [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum|Guggenheim Blog]], February 7, 2014.</ref> is an American graphic designer, art director and illustrator, and founder of creative agency & Walsh.\n\n==Early life and education==\nWalsh was born in [[New York (state)|New York]]<ref>Ryan & Tina Essmaker, [https://thegreatdiscontent.com/jessica-walsh \u201cJessica Walsh,\u201d] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140521070210/https://thegreatdiscontent.com/jessica-walsh |date=2014-05-21 }} The Great Discontent, September 18, 2012.</ref> and raised in nearby [[Ridgefield, Connecticut]].<ref name=\"cdover\"/> She began coding and designing websites at age 11<ref name=\"srodd\">Scott Rodd, [http://observer.com/2014/04/jessica-walsh-graphic-designer-profile/#axzz324bfL7ST \u201cFont of Youth: Jessica Walsh, Graphic Design\u2019s \u2018It\u2019 Girl,\u201d] ''[[New York Observer]]'', April 10, 2014.</ref> and went on to study graphic design at the [[Rhode Island School of Design]] (RISD).<ref name=\"lmallonee\">Laura C. Mallonee, [http://scenemag.com/2014/05/jessica-walsh-art-director-of-sagmeister-walsh/ \u201cJessica Walsh: Art Director of Sagmeister & Walsh,\u201d] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160514171322/http://scenemag.com/2014/05/jessica-walsh-art-director-of-sagmeister-walsh/ |date=2016-05-14 }} ''Scene'' magazine, May 2014.</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Sagmeister & Walsh===\nAfter earning her Bachelor of Fine Arts from RISD in 2008, Walsh moved to [[New York City]]. to intern at the notable design firm [[Pentagram (design studio)|Pentagram]]. She turned down a job at Apple where she was offered nearly $100,000 annually to accept the internship under Paula Scher at Pentagram, where she would stay for nearly a year.<ref name=\"srodd\"/><ref name=\"aallsopp\">Ashleigh Allsopp, [http://www.digitalartsonline.co.uk/news/illustration/interview-jessica-walsh-talks-upcoming-projects-favourite-designs-naked-photo/ \u201cInterview: Jessica Walsh discusses play, her favourite designs, future plans & that photo,\u201d] Digital Arts, May 9, 2013.</ref> She then worked as an associate art director at ''[[Print (magazine)|Print]]'' magazine<ref name=\"aallsopp\"/> and had design work and illustrations featured in various books, magazines and newspapers, including the ''[[New York Times]]'' and ''[[New York Times Magazine]]''.<ref name=\"envyindex\">[http://www.thelmagazine.com/gyrobase/the-envy-index-25-under-25/Content?oid=2196532&storyPage=9 \u201cThe Envy Index: 25 Under 25,\u201d] ''[[The L Magazine]]'', December 7, 2011.</ref><ref name=\"sgruenwedel\">Stefan Gruenwedel, [http://www.adobe.com/inspire/2012/12/interview-jessica-walsh.html \u201cHand-crafted photo illustrations of Jessica Walsh,\u201d] [[adobe.com]], December 2012.</ref> In reflections about her time at Print magazine, she identifies it as one of the best things to happen in her career as it was how she found and developed her personal style.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eyeondesign.aiga.org/the-first-thing-i-ever-designed-how-jessica-walsh-developed-her-distinct-colorful-paper-set-style-at-print/|title=How Jessica Walsh Developed Her Distinct + Colorful Style of Art Direction at Print|last=Morley|first=Madeleine|date=May 29, 2017|website=Eye on Design|access-date=February 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Walsh met [[Stefan Sagmeister]]. He looked through her portfolio and offered her a job at his design studio, Sagmeister Inc.<ref name=\"srodd\"/><ref name=\"lmallonee\"/> In June 2012, after two years at the firm, Walsh was made partner, at age 25.<ref name=\"jedwards\">Jim Edwards, [http://www.businessinsider.com/why-this-new-york-design-agency-makes-its-employees-pose-naked-for-official-staff-photos-2013-5?op=1#!KvyxW \u201cWhy This New York Design Agency Makes Its Employees Pose Naked For Staff Photos,\u201d] ''[[Business Insider]]'', June 2, 2013.</ref><ref>Patrick Burgoyne, [http://www.creativereview.co.uk/cr-blog/2012/june/getting-naked-with-sagmeister \u201cThe perils of getting naked with Sagmeister,\u201d] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140521033248/http://www.creativereview.co.uk/cr-blog/2012/june/getting-naked-with-sagmeister |date=2014-05-21 }} Creative Review, June 1, 2012.</ref> In homage to a nude self-portrait Sagmeister had sent out to announce the formation of his own firm 19 years prior, the new partners released a photo of themselves naked in their office to announce the renaming of the firm to Sagmeister & Walsh.<ref name=\"jedwards\"/>\n\nBlending handcraft, photography and painting with digital design,<ref name=\"cdover\"/><ref>Tina Berglund, [http://radarmagazine.se/people/interview-people/jessica-walsh/ \u201cJessica Walsh,\u201d] ''Radar'', December 4, 2013.</ref> Walsh works primarily on branding, typography, website design and art installations.<ref name=\"sgruenwedel\"/> Her signature style has been described as \"bold, emotional and provocative\"<ref name=\"lmallonee\"/> with the occasional surrealistic flourish,<ref>Laura Neilson, [http://www.wearedesignbureau.com/projects/the-inspiration-issue-jessica-walsh/ \u201cSurrealism,\u201d] ''Design Bureau'', August 29, 2013.</ref> and her art has been said to look \"hand-made and at times quite daring.\"<ref name=\"sgruenwedel\"/> Walsh has worked on projects for clients including [[Levi's]], [[A\u00efshti|Aizone]], [[Adobe Systems|Adobe]] and Colab Eyewear,<ref name=\"srodd\"/><ref>Carey Dunne, [http://www.fastcodesign.com/3027274/innovation-by-design/sagmeister-walsh-compete-in-a-gameshow-to-recreate-adobes-logo \u201cSagmeister & Walsh Compete In A Gameshow To Re-Create Adobe\u2019s Logo,\u201d] ''[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]]'', March 6, 2014.</ref> and rebranding efforts for [[The Jewish Museum of New York]] and the [[Aldrich Contemporary Art Museum]] in Connecticut.<ref name=\"cdover\"/><ref>Carey Dunne, [http://www.fastcodesign.com/3029868/sagmeister-walsh-rebrand-the-jewish-museum-using-sacred-geometry \u201cSagmeister & Walsh Rebrand The Jewish Museum, Using Sacred Geometry,\u201d] ''Fast Company'', April 30, 2014.</ref> Walsh and Sagmeister collaborated on ''Six Things: Sagmeister & Walsh'', an exhibition that opened at the Jewish Museum in March 2013, and ran for five months. For the exhibit, an exploration of happiness, they created a sound-activated sculpture and five short films.<ref>Anna Carnick, [https://tmagazine.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/03/14/six-things-sagmeister-walsh/?_php=true&_type=blogs&action=click&module=Search&region=searchResults&mabReward=relbias%3Ar&url=http%3A%2F%2Fquery.nytimes.com%2Fsearch%2Fsitesearch%2F%3Faction%3Dclick%26region%3DMasthead%26pgtype%3DHomepage%26module%3DSearchSubmit%26contentCollection%3DHomepage%26t%3Dqry319%23%2Fjessica+walsh&_r=0 \u201cSix Things: Sagmeister & Walsh,\u201d] ''[[T: The New York Times Style Magazine]]'', March 14, 2013.</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, Walsh announced she was leaving Sagmeister & Walsh and forming her own studio, & Walsh. Walsh has said that the studio is a fulfillment of her dreams as a teen to run her own business and the studio will become one of 36 female-led creative studios in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adweek.com/agencies/famed-designer-jessica-walsh-starts-her-own-creative-agency/|title=Famed Designer Jessica Walsh Starts Her Own Creative Agency|last=ago|first=Minda Smiley{{!}}6 days|website=www.adweek.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref>\n\n===''40 Days of Dating''===\nIn 2013, Walsh and fellow designer and friend Tim Goodman decided to date for 40 days to see if they could overcome their relationship issues and fall in love. They documented the social experiment on a blog, ''[http://fortydaysofdating.com 40 Days of Dating]'', launched in July 2013.<ref name=\"srodd\"/><ref name=\"mruiz\">Michelle Ruiz, [http://www.cosmopolitan.com/celebrity/exclusive/forty-days-of-dating-interview \u201c40 Days of Dating Couple Endorse Lizzy Caplan, Paul Bettany for Movie Version,\u201d] ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'', September 25, 2013.</ref> In support of the blog, which earned more than 5 million unique visitors in less than a year,<ref name=\"srodd\"/> they appeared in segments on talk shows ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]]''<ref>[http://www.today.com/health/longtime-friends-experiment-date-40-days-8C11111046 \u201cLongtime friends experiment, date for 40 days,\u201d] ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]]'', [[NBC]], September 9, 2013.</ref> and ''[[The View (U.S. TV series)|The View]]''.<ref>''[[The View (U.S. TV series)|The View]]'', [http://abc.go.com/shows/the-view/episode-guide/2013-12/13-friday-dec-13-2013 Season 18, Episode 69], [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], December 13, 2013.</ref> In September 2013, [[Warner Brothers]] purchased the film rights, with a screenplay to be written by [[Lorene Scafaria]], and [[Michael Sucsy]] attached to direct.<ref name=\"edodds\">Eric Dodds, [http://entertainment.time.com/2013/09/19/40-days-online-stars-prepare-for-hollywood-ending/ \u201c\u201940 Days\u2019 Online Stars Prepare for Hollywood Ending,\u201d] ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', September 19, 2013.</ref><ref>Mike Fleming, Jr., [https://www.deadline.com/2013/09/warner-bros-buys-rights-to-40-days-of-dating-blog-michael-sucsy-to-direct-film/ \u201cWarner Bros Buys Rights To \u201940 Days of Dating\u2019 Blog: Michael Sucsy To Direct,\u201d] ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'', September 17, 2013.</ref> Walsh and Goodman will serve as consulting writers on the script<ref name=\"mruiz\"/> and also wrote a book for [[Abrams Books|Abrams]], ''40 Days of Dating: An Experiment'', out in early 2015.<ref name=\"srodd\"/><ref name=\"lmallonee\"/>\n\n=== ''12 Kinds of Kindness'' ===\nIn 2016, Walsh and Goodman began a second project together, which they described as a \"12-step experiment designed to open [their] hearts, eyes, and minds\". They set up twelve tasks in which they displayed kindness to people and recorded the results. The experiment was live from January 13 to March 15, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://12kindsofkindness.com/about/|title=About \u2013 12 Kinds of Kindness|website=12kindsofkindness.com|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref>\n\n=== Ladies Wine and Design ===\nWalsh started Ladies, Wine & Design, a nonprofit organization to encourage women to work together rather than compete, in 2016. {{As of|September 2019}}, the organization has 273 local chapters around the world.<ref name=lwddezeen>{{cite web|url=https://www.dezeen.com/2019/09/27/jessica-walsh-design-interview/|title=Jessica Walsh: Design Interview|first=Bridget|last=Cogley|work=Dezeen|date=September 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Other work===\nWalsh teaches design and typography at the [[School of Visual Arts]] in New York.<ref name=\"msilverberg\">Michael Silverberg, [http://www.printmag.com/featured/some-uncomfortable-thoughts-about-sagmeister-walshs-new-identity/ \u201cSome Uncomfortable Thoughts About Sagmeister & Walsh\u2019s New Identity,\u201d] ''[[Print (magazine)|Print]]'', January 23, 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.sva.edu/faculty/jessica-walsh \u201cOur Faculty: Jessica Walsh,\u201d] sva.edu. Accessed May 20, 2014.</ref> She is represented by [[Creative Artists Agency]].<ref name=\"edodds\"/>\n\n==Exhibitions==\n* ''Sagmeister: Another Show About Advertising and Promotion Materials'', [[Les Arts D\u00e9coratifs]], [[The Louvre]], [[Paris, France]], 2011-12<ref>[http://ndagallery.cooperhewitt.org/gallery/Les-Arts-Decoratifs-Poster/4808685 \u201cLes Arts Decoratifs Poster,\u201d] National Design Awards. Retrieved May 20, 2014.</ref>\n* ''The Happy Show'', [[Institute of Contemporary Art, Philadelphia|Institute of Contemporary Art]], [[Philadelphia, PA]]; [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles|Museum of Contemporary Art]], [[Los Angeles, CA]]; [[Chicago Cultural Center]], [[Chicago, IL]]; [[Design Exchange]], [[Toronto]], [[Canada]], 2012<ref name=\"klala\">Kisa Lala, [https://www.huffingtonpost.com/kisa-lala/moving-against-type-stefan-sagmeister_b_3321523.html \u201cMoving Against Type: Stefan Sagmeister,\u201d] ''[[Huffington Post]]'', June 19, 2013.</ref>\n* ''Six Things: Sagmeister & Walsh'', [[The Jewish Museum of New York|The Jewish Museum]], [[New York, NY]], 2013<ref name=\"klala\"/>\n*''Sagmeister & Walsh: Beauty'', [[Museum of Applied Arts, Vienna|MAK \u2013 Museum of Applied Arts Vienna]], 2018/2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mak.at/en_sagmeister_walsh|title=Exhibition Sagmeister & Walsh: Beauty - MAK Museum Vienna|website=www.mak.at|language=en|access-date=2018-10-25}}</ref>\n\n==Honors and awards==\n* New Star of Design, ''Computer Arts'', 2010<ref>[http://www.creativebloq.com/computer-arts/new-stars-design-12098950 \u201cThe new stars of design,\u201d] ''Computer Arts'', December 15, 2009.</ref>\n* Society of Publication Designers award, 2010<ref name=\"sgruenwedel\"/>\n* Young Gun Award, [[Art Directors Club of New York|Art Directors Club]], 2011<ref name=\"gdusa\">[http://www.gdusa.com/issue_2013/january/ptw/jessica-walsh.php \u201cPeople to Watch: Jessica Walsh,\u201d] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140521032859/http://www.gdusa.com/issue_2013/january/ptw/jessica-walsh.php |date=2014-05-21 }} ''GD USA'', January 2013.</ref>\n* New Visual Artist Award, ''[[Print (magazine)|Print]]'' magazine, 2011<ref name=\"msilverberg\"/>\n* The Envy Index: 25 Under 25, ''[[The L Magazine]]'', 2011<ref name=\"envyindex\"/> \n* Type Director\u2019s Club Award, [[Les Arts D\u00e9coratifs]] poster, 2012<ref name=\"sgruenwedel\"/>\n* 25 People Shaping the Future of Design, ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'', 2013<ref>Emily Anne Kuriyama, [http://www.complex.com/art-design/2013/10/future-of-design/stefan-sagmeister-jessica-walsh \u201c25 People Shaping the Future of Design,\u201d] ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'', October 14, 2013.</ref>\n* People to Watch, ''GD USA'', 2013<ref name=\"gdusa\"/>\n* [[Webby Award]], Best Home/Welcome Page, Sagmeister & Walsh, 2014<ref>Abigail Tracy, [http://www.inc.com/abigail-tracy/webby-awards-name-best-of-the-internet.html \u201cWebby Awards Honor the Best of the Internet,\u201d] ''[[Inc. (magazine)|Inc.]]'', April 28, 2014.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWalsh lives in New York City with her husband, cinematographer Zak Mulligan.<ref name=\"srodd\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.sagmeisterwalsh.com/ Sagmeister & Walsh website]\n* [http://fortydaysofdating.com/ ''40 Days of Dating'' blog]\n*[http://www.12kindsofkindness.com www.12kindsofkindness.com]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walsh, Jessica}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American graphic designers]]\n[[Category:Women graphic designers]]\n[[Category:Rhode Island School of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:School of Visual Arts faculty]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York City]]\n", "name_user": "Adqlth", "label": "safe", "comment": "updated her website since she started her own agency", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jessica_Walsh"}
